    {
      "id": "https://www.nerdwallet.com/article/credit-cards/what-is-cardless-and-are-its-credit-cards-right-for-you",
      "title": "What Is Cardless, and Are Its Credit Cards Right for You? - NerdWallet",
      "url": "https://www.nerdwallet.com/article/credit-cards/what-is-cardless-and-are-its-credit-cards-right-for-you",
      "publishedDate": "2025-03-20T14:11:08.000Z",
      "author": "Sara Rathner, Gregory Karp",
      "text": "Cardless is a credit card provider to individual brands. The San Francisco-based company was founded in 2019. Its cards are issued through FDIC-insured First Electronic Bank in Salt Lake City. (And despite its name, Cardless issues physical credit cards.) The company has two co-branded cards with LATAM Airlines, a South American carrier; two cards with Qatar Airways; two with Colombia-based Avianca Airlines; plus a card with TAP Air Portugal. In addition, Cardless has a co-branded card in partnership with mall company Simon Property Group and American Express, as well as a co-branded small-business card in partnership with online retailer Alibaba.com. Cardless first earned a foothold in creating cards for professional sports teams, such as the Boston Celtics basketball team and soccer's Manchester United, although those cards have all since been shut down as the company has shifted its focus largely to travel. So Cardless is a legitimate company and is safe to consider doing business with. Its products offer familiar credit card features and reward structures, along with perks specific to the partner brand, like earning airline miles through your spending. That doesn‚Äôt mean all of Cardless' products will be right for you, or that you‚Äôll have a good experience. Also, as of this writing, Cardless notes that you can have only one of its cards ever ‚Äî even if one of your previous cards from the company has been closed. (An exception to this rule is if you previously had one of those co-branded sports teams cards that was shuttered, in which case Cardless says you'll likely be able to apply for another card from its portfolio \"in the near future.\") Here's what else to know. Are Cardless credit cards good? As with any co-branded credit cards, Cardless‚Äô cards are most useful if you‚Äôre loyal to one of the brands it has partnered with. For instance, if you fly often on Qatar Airways, TAP Air Portugal or LATAM Airlines, you‚Äôre more likely to get value out of the appropriate card, especially if you can make use of perks like free checked bags or airport lounge access. But it's also worth noting that a general travel credit card ‚Äî that is, one that's not co-branded with an airline ‚Äî can often be a more flexible and valuable pick. These general cards likely won't come with perks specific to your favorite airline, but on the other hand, you won't be locked into a specific airline when it comes to redeeming your rewards. ü§ì Nerdy Tip Keep in mind that TAP Air Portugal is already a travel partner with Capital One, Qatar Airways is a travel partner with Citi, and Avianca is a partner with both issuers, as well as American Express and Wells Fargo. If you have an eligible travel card from one of those banks, you can transfer your points from that card to those respective airlines. Cardless credit cards for travel Qatar Airways Qatar Airways Privilege Club Visa Infinite Credit Card Qatar Airways Privilege Club Visa Signature Credit Card Annual fee $499. $99. Sign-up ",
      "image": "https://www.nerdwallet.com/tachyon/2024/05/GettyImages-1822433835.jpg?resize=1440%2C864",
      "favicon": "https://www.nerdwallet.com/cdn/favicon.ico"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://pear.vc/companies/cardless/",
      "title": "Cardless - Pear VC",
      "url": "https://pear.vc/companies/cardless/",
      "publishedDate": "2025-01-14T21:46:57.000Z",
      "author": "",
      "text": "\n \n \n \n \n Cardless gives brands and tech companies a way to launch custom co-branded credit cards. Their mission is to make credit more engaging, rewarding, and accessible. Cardless partners with brands to power products for their customers by refining the consumer credit experience, building products that help serve the customer‚Äôs long-term good, provide meaningful rewards, and allow for rapid iteration. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Cardless + Pear \n Pear first met Cardless co-founders, Michael and Scott, when they applied to Pear‚Äôs 2019 Accelerator ( PearX). We believed in their vision to revolutionize how brands interact with their most loyal customers. \n We‚Äôve supported them at every step of their journey, helping them build an incredible team and closing key partnerships with the Cleveland Cavaliers and Manchester United. \n \n Company Details \n \n Headquarters \n San Francisco, CA \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n ‚ÄúThe magic of Pear is their intense focus on us as people and founders. For us, Pear was the perfect bridge from a little idea in the back of our heads that everyone thought was crazy to a $2.7M seed round and then a Series A. They didn‚Äôt judge our idea or come up with reasons why it wouldn‚Äôt work; they pushed us to figure out how to make it work, giving us some hard-won advice along the journey between pre-seed and seed. When Michael and I went into Pear‚Äôs office, it felt like they were entrepreneurs, too. Pear‚Äôs scrappiness, energy, and humility was really attractive to us and has become part of the culture of our own company.‚Äù \n Scott Kazmierowicz \n Co-founder &amp; CEO, Cardless \n \n \n \n \n \n \n Grid Item Logo \n \n Rescale: \n \n \n Grid Item Background Image \n \n \n \n Grid Item Featured Image \n \n \n \n Company Website \n https://www.cardless.com/ \n \n Jobs Website \n https://www.cardless.com/careers \n \n",
      "favicon": "https://pear.vc/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/cropped-Pear-Favicon-32x32.png"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://techcrunch.com/2024/11/26/cardless-swipes-up-30m-to-build-a-new-generation-of-co-branded-credit-cards/",
      "title": "Cardless swipes up $30M to build a new generation of co-branded ...",
      "url": "https://techcrunch.com/2024/11/26/cardless-swipes-up-30m-to-build-a-new-generation-of-co-branded-credit-cards/",
      "publishedDate": "2024-11-26T00:00:00.000Z",
      "author": "Ingrid Lunden",
      "text": "\n More than a quarter of all U.S. residents use co-branded credit cards to get discounts and other extras from brands they use regularly. But not all is rosy in the world of loyalty commerce. Major brands like Uber, Starbucks, and Walmart have all pulled back from such projects over the years after failing to see the returns they were expecting. Now, tapping into the innovations of embedded finance, a startup called Cardless believes it has figured out how to make card schemes work better. \n Today it‚Äôs announcing $30 million in funding to expand that business. Activant Capital, a previous backer, is leading the round, with Mischief (a fund co-founded by Plaid‚Äôs Zach Perret), Industry Ventures, Thayer Ventures, Assurant, and strategic backer Amex Ventures also participating. \n Cardless is not disclosing its valuation with this round ‚Äî nor is it indicating whether it is flat, up, or down on its previous valuation. For some context on that, when it last raised money ‚Äî $40 million in 2021 ‚Äî the valuation was just over $350 million.¬† \n In the interim, the San Francisco startup has been growing. The company, which provides Visa, Mastercard, and American Express card options, said that revenues grew fivefold in the past 12 months, which was level with its growth rate a year before ‚Äî exact numbers not being disclosed. Although it works with global companies to reach end users, the company‚Äôs target market is the U.S. It has no plans to go abroad for now. It also works with large and smaller brands based out of the U.S. itself. Recent customers have included Qatar Airways and Alibaba, with the latter aiming services at small and medium businesses in the U.S. that use Alibaba to buy goods that they in turn use or resell. \n Cardless‚Äôs unique selling point is not that it helps companies build co-branded cards. There are dozens of companies, from newer tech companies like Marqeta through to incumbents like traditional banks, that already provide that.¬† \n Instead, Cardless‚Äôs pitch is that it does this on a much more efficient platform. The brands in question can build more customized card experiences to sign up and onboard users within weeks between planning and execution. They can subsequently build rewards and observe how those products are performing. \n ‚ÄúThe credit card space is ubiquitous from the consumer angle, but from brands‚Äô point of view, it is ripe to be disrupted,‚Äù said Michael Spelfogel, president and co-founder of Cardless, who said that 11 banks today operate ‚Äúthe vast majority‚Äù of co-branded credit cards in what is a $77 billion industry. \n Features include the ability to set up card applications within existing apps, and then subsequently to integrate card management into those apps.¬† \n Once created, rewards and other marketing can be incorporated and modified through a dashboard. Fraud detection and security are incorporated into the platform, as are usage analytics to help product managers understand what is working and what is not.¬† \n There ",
      "image": "https://techcrunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/GettyImages-160770192-e1687445475790.jpg?resize=1200,818",
      "favicon": "https://techcrunch.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/cropped-cropped-favicon-gradient.png?w=32"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://www.builtinsf.com/company/cardless",
      "title": "Cardless San Francisco Office: Careers, Perks + Culture",
      "url": "https://www.builtinsf.com/company/cardless",
      "publishedDate": "2025-01-01T00:00:00.000Z",
      "author": "",
      "text": "\nWe partner with brands to help them launch their own co-branded credit card with customizable rewards programs.\n \n Cardless is a fintech startup located in San Francisco. Our mission is to make consumer credit more accessible, useful, and engaging, and we do that by partnering with brands to help them launch financial products. \n",
      "favicon": "https://www.builtinsf.com/companies/images/favicon.png"
    }
